\subtree{\title{Conceptual realism and objective idealism}

  \p{Problem with [Cartesian representationalism](descartes): it wants to \em{separately} understand minds (representings) and things (representeds). This creates a dualism when it becomes hard to understand their relationships (knowledge \em{of} the facts \em{by} the knowings, action \em{on} the facts \em{by} the will). [Kant](kant) founded German \em{idealism} by removing this dualism, viewing the world as in conceptual shape. This is crazy if you think concepts are mental representations: Hegel's non-psychological conception of the conceptual holds something as conceptually contentful if it stands in relations of [material](int-0007) incompatibility and consequence[^trm] to other such contentful items.
  }


