  \p{Genuine knowledge is when the same content shows up in \em{both} different forms. A fact is a thought that is true. They are not different kinds of things, as in the Cartesian or even Kantian picture. Kant only acknowledged the conceptual articulation of the subjective - Hegel pushes this further by understanding conceptual content such that the objective is likewise conceptually articulated.}

  \p{Idealists are typically dismissed by acknowledging there \em{was} an objective world before there were any knowing subjects and there \em{would have been} such a world if there \em{never had been} any knowing subjects. This concern is addressed by distinguishing [Sense dependence vs reference](int-0017): there is a reference dependence between facts/objects/properties and the discursive practice of knowing subjects which is acyclic, but there is a \em{mutual} sense dependence between them: one cannot \em{understand} what one is \em{saying} when one says \em{that} there are objects/properties without \em{understanding} what one is \em{doing} in certain social practices (e.g. referring, predicating).
  }
  \p{[^trm]: "determinate negation" and "mediation"
  }

