\p{Brandom reads [Hegel](hegel) as trying to synthesize the pre-modern and modern insights to avoid fetishization and alienation.}

\p{Autonomy is a social status: an authority to \em{make} oneself responsible (i.e. to \em{institute} a further normative status). It is a kind of independence to make oneself dependent by acknowledging a commitment. Kant thinks normative have a \em{duty} to acknowledge the autonomy of normative subjects. He thinks by our nature we just \em{come} with this duty and this authority. }

\p{Hegel derives these social statuses from reciprocal recognition. To genuinely make one self responsible, one must not only acknowledge that commitment but also acknowledge others as holding one responsible (furthermore, they must actually attribute that responsibility, \em{taking} one to be responsible). Hegel diagnoses some defective social situations as due to normative attitudes with asymmetric recognitive relations (e.g. superiority/subordination). Thus the attitudes of others (what one is \em{for others}) is as essential to what one acknowledges, i.e. what one is \em{for oneself}.
}
\p{Meaning and belief are normative concepts. Meanings are norms for the formation of beliefs (i.e. adoption of propositional attitudes). Hegel thinks in terms of "the Concept" - a holistic constellation of ever-evolving meanings and beliefs each sensitive to changes in the other. The mutual dependence of meaning and correctness (in contrast to Carnap's [language-theory distinction](phil-016R)) was rediscovered by Wittgenstein and Quine's Two Dogmas.
}
\p{Kant understands sense impressions as inexhaustible by some finite set of judgments (there's no bit that cannot be conceptualized, but conceptualizing \em{all} is an infinite task). Hegel interprets the same phenomenon as the \strong{instability} of any set of determinate empirical concepts. If we unpack the norms for endorsing any finite set of judgments, we will be led to incompatible doxastic commitments.
}
}
\subtree{\title{Semantics: recollection and representation}

  \p{How to synthesize the premodern notion of us \em{finding} norms vs the modern notion of us \em{making} them? Common law judges provide a model for how this works.
  }
  \p{Retrospectively, a judge gives a rational reconstruction of what some legal concept means by looking at precedent and \em{finding out} what the norms were. This seems suspicious as a judge can tell whatever story they want - the previous use of a concept doesn't objectively determine its rightful future use. But this is one-sided: the judge's \em{responsibility} to the past is administered by \em{future} judges, as they will consider the ruling in context and decide whether it was itself precedential / progressive / responsive to the actual norms or not (e.g. if the reconstruction depended on 'what the judge had for breakfast'). So law is both \em{made} (viewed prospectively, via making rational reconstructions) and \em{found} (viewed retrospectively, as part of a future rational reconstruction) by judges.
  }
  \p{Hegel's term for 'rational reconstruction' is recollection: a distinctive kind of making that is finding. This is a pragmatic account of institution of norms by attitudes (yet compatible with attitudes governed by statuses).
  }
  \subtree{\title{Conceptual idealism}

    \p{Synthesis of conceptual realism and objective idealism - an account of the relations between objective reality and representational appearances in terms of the process of rectifying and (further) determining the conceptual contents of the representings.
    }
    \ul{
      \li{Semantics (conceptual content / consciousness)}
      \ul{
        \li{Hegelian senses (what things are for consciousness) are responsible to Hegelian referents (what things are in themselves) via representational responsibility.}
      }\li{Pragmatics (normative force / self-consciousness) }
      \ul{
        \li{Normative attitudes instantiate normative statuses. }
        \li{They also are responsible \em{to} normative statuses via representational responsibility. }
      }\li{Attitudes are responsible to content.}}
  }}
\subtree{\title{Postmodernity: reconciling traditional and modern insights}

  \p{Conceptual \em{content} arises from normative \em{force}. Recollecting \em{takes} objective conceptual norms to be acknowledged by discursive practitioners and thereby \em{makes} those attitudes intelligible as adopting normative statuses.
  }
  \p{Understanding the conditions of having determinate thoughts/intentions commits us to adopting to one another practical \em{recognitive} attitudes (e.g. forgiveness, confession, trust).[^k] Reciprocal recognition (over space or, as in the case of common law judges, time) requires a community built on trust. The social determinateness of meaning requires me, by writing something down and meaning something by it, to trust my being interpreted / redescribed by others.
  }
  \p{[^k]: This is akin to Kant deriving morality from a proper understanding of intentional agency (making explicit commitments already present in any discursive activity).
  }
}
